  <br>
 I'm having problems with inking my pencil drawings. On the PolyCarbon homepage Patrick mentions he always uses French Curves. So I bought some but I'm lost by how to use them effectively. Sure they work for a little part of my line, but when it changes direction, I have to shift everything right? But that usually leaves me with a dot where I put my pen down again and also, the line's arc changes.. Does anyone have any tips? <br>
 <br>
 Or would you recommend doing the inking on Adobe Illustrator? I guess I'd just like to be able to do it the old-fashioned way. <br>
<br>
 Thanks for any input.<br>
<br>
 -Jonny Danger <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=eddavids22>EdDavids22</A> at: 9/25/01 7:54:21 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ucaptainmeth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Captain Meth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/25/01 8:26:14 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.methart.com/t_meth2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Inking</span><hr size=1> Well, the old fashioned way is much more rewarding.  You'll learn better skills if you do it via that method.<br>
<br>
As far as the curves go, yes, you're going to have to stop and lift them up and move them around when you're inking.  I don't use mine very often, but I have a steadier hand than some people.  If you're finding the curves to be bothersome, try drawing some curves on another sheet of paper, and then try inking those to get practice at it.  It'll help out big time. <p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
